<p> 
</p>
<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Sixth session  
Agenda item 3 
</p>
<p><b>PROMOTION AND PROTECTION OF ALL HUMAN RIGHTS,  
CIVIL, POLITICAL, ECONOMIC, SOCIAL AND CULTURAL  
    RIGHTS, INCLUDING THE RIGHT TO DEVELOPMENT 
</b></p>
<p><b>Argentina</b>*<b>, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile</b>*<b>, Colombia</b>*<b>, Ecuador</b>*<b>, Haiti</b>*<b>,  
Honduras</b>*<b>, Nicaragua, Panama</b>*<b>, Paraguay</b>*<b>, Peru, Uruguay:   
                                                 draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>Creation of a working group to elaborate a set of human rights voluntary goals  
to be launched on the occasion of the celebration of the sixtieth anniversary of  
                                    the Universal Declaration of Human Rights 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council</i>, </p>
<p><i> Guided</i> by the purposes, principles and provisions of the Charter of the United Nations, 
</p>
<p><i> Reaffirming</i> the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, 
</p>
<p><i> Recognizing </i>the relevance of the core human rights international instruments and their 
optional protocols, 
</p>
<p><i> Bearing in mind</i> the activities to be undertaken in celebration of the sixtieth anniversary of 
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights of 1948, 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*  Non-member States of the Human Rights Council. </p>

 <p></p>
<p><i> Taking note with appreciation</i> of the proposal by Brazil, with the support of other member 
States of the Southern Common Market (MERCOSUR), Argentina, Paraguay and Uruguay, as 
well as Chile as associate member, to create a working group to elaborate a set of human rights 
goals to be pursued, inspired by the Millennium Development Goals, 
</p>
<p><i> Taking into account</i> that the above initiative could bring more visibility and effectiveness 
to the United Nations human rights system with a view to the promotion and protection of 
human rights, 
</p>
<p> <i>Considering</i> that the Working Group might examine, inter alia, the following set of goals: 
</p>
<p> (<i>a</i>) Universal ratification of the core international human rights instruments; 
</p>
<p> (<i>b</i>) Elaboration, in each country, of a national human rights programme, and the creation 
of national bodies responsible for human rights issues, in accordance with the Vienna 
Declaration and Programme of Action of 1993; 
</p>
<p> (<i>c</i>) Adoption of a legal and institutional framework at the national level to ensure the 
promotion and protection of all human rights, including the elimination of torture and other 
cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment; 
</p>
<p> (<i>d</i>) Definition, within the framework of national human rights programmes, of targets 
and actions in the field of capacity-building as well as a programme of human rights education 
and identification of needs and shortcomings related to international cooperation; and 
</p>
<p> (<i>e</i>) Assessment of needs and actions to eliminate racism, racial discrimination, 
xenophobia and related intolerance, including aggravated or multiple forms of discrimination. 
</p>
<p> 1.<i> Decides</i> to establish an open-ended intergovernmental working group to elaborate, 
on a consensual basis, a proposal of human rights voluntary goals, to promote the effective 
implementation of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and States&#8217; international 
obligations in the field of human rights, to be launched in 10 December 2008 during the 
celebration of the sixtieth anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights of 1948; </p>

 <p></p>
<p> 2. <i>Requests</i> the Working Group to meet in a formal setting for 10 working 
</p>
<p>meetings, as well as to hold informal meetings, as appropriate, and to report to the Council 
by September 2008; 
</p>
<p> 3.<i> Welcomes</i> participation in the process, as appropriate, by representatives of the 
United Nations and of regional human rights systems, as well as all relevant stakeholders; 
</p>
<p> 4.<i> Requests</i> the Secretary-General to give the open-ended intergovernmental 
working group all necessary human and financial assistance for the effective fulfilment of its 
mandate. 
</p>
<p>----- </p>

